seid@seya:~/spare/client$ docker build -t client .
Successfully built 8b0f4dbc13a8
Successfully tagged client:latest
seid@seya:~/spare/client$

The "Build Context": When you run docker build .,
 the "Docker Engine" takes all the files in your current folder and sends them to the Docker daemon.

image build done
The Image is that read-only snapshot containing the OS, your node_modules, and your built React code.

The Execution: Inside the temporary container used for building, the engine executes npm install.
 This happens in the isolated environment of the container,
 meaning the node_modules created inside the image are specifically built for the Linux environment of the container,
 not your host PC.

React app → static files
Nginx → serves those files
Nginx port → 80 (default)

container port in this case is 80 nginx defalut port 
hot machine port you can assign any number lets say 3000

#Start a new container from an image
docker run -d -p 3000:80 <image -id > 
docker run -d -p 3000:80 8b0f4dbc13a8

real MERN systems  always include:

Frontend (React)
Backend (Node/Express)
Database (PostgreSQL)

====               ============                 ============
Create backend Dockerfile
Go to your server folder:

cd server
touch Dockerfile

industry-standard Node/Express Dockerfile:
-----------------------------------------------------
# Base image
FROM node:18-alpine

# Set working directory
WORKDIR /app

# Copy dependency files
COPY package.json package-lock.json ./

# Install dependencies
RUN npm install

# Copy all source code
COPY . .

# Expose backend port
EXPOSE 5000

# Start server
CMD ["node", "index.js"]
--------------------------------------------------------


creating docker compose a controller connector we can say 
STEP NEXT

#Create docker-compose.yml
in the project root directory

touch docker-compose.yml

-----------------------------------------
version: "3.8"

services:

  client:
    build: ./client
    ports:
      - "3000:80"

  server:
    build: ./server
    ports:
      - "5000:4000"
    environment:
      - DB_HOST=db

  db:
    image: postgres:15
    restart: always
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER: admin
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: admin
      POSTGRES_DB: appdb
    ports:
      - "5432:5432"

===========================================================================================
#Run everything together
docker-compose up --build

Now you get:

React → http://localhost:3000
API → http://localhost:5000
DB → running internally
  client:
    build: ./client
    ports:
      - "3000:80"

build: ./client: Instead of you running docker build manually,
 Compose looks into your /client folder for that Multi-stage Dockerfile you wrote and builds the image automatically.

"3000:80": This connects your physical computer (port 3000) to the Nginx server inside the container (port 80). When you type localhost:3000 in your browser, Nginx answers.


What actually happens when you run docker-compose

When you run:

docker-compose up --build

Docker will:

1. Pull PostgreSQL image
postgres:15
2. Create container
db container running PostgreSQL server
3. Initialize database automatically

Based on:

POSTGRES_DB=appdb
POSTGRES_USER=admin
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=admin


React (client)  → talks to → Node (server) → talks to → PostgreSQL (db)


docker-compose up --build

Error happend today 
 File "/usr/lib/python3/dist-packages/compose/service.py", line 1579, in get_container_data_volumes
    container.image_config['ContainerConfig'].get('Volumes') or {}
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
KeyError: 'ContainerConfig'
Reason 
 Docker Compose tried to:

reuse old container config
merge old volumes/state
failed → ContainerConfig missing

solution:-
run this command to clean old containers 
CLEAN RESET
docker-compose down -v --remove-orphans

CLEAN DOCKER SYSTEM (VERY EFFECTIVE)
docker system prune -a

REBUILD FROM SCRATCH
docker-compose up --build
